Business Type Foundation — Implementation Plan

Context

business_type already exists and works as a categorization key: it's on the tenant record, gets set onto the JWT auth payload (netlify/functions/utils/auth.mjs), and is typed loosely as businessType: string on the user object (src/contexts/AuthContext.tsx:14). The gap is that valid values are a hardcoded array in two places, there's no registry to attach per-type defaults to, and the only consumer (src/App.tsx:689,725,1010) branches directly on the string instead of reading from config.

This round: turn business_type into a real registry with admin-manageable defaults, make it editable on existing tenants, and migrate the existing physical_store nav logic onto the existing module/feature access system (modules.ts / tenant_module_quotas), rather than a separate nav-specific config key.

Decisions made for this round (flag if any should change before building)


New table is named business_types — matches the existing field name, no renaming of business_type anywhere.
config_defaults is JSONB with no enforced schema beyond what's documented below — extendable later without migrations.
Business type becomes editable on an existing tenant.
Module/feature defaults from business_types.config_defaults are applied only at tenant creation. Changing business_type on an existing tenant does not auto-overwrite already-configured module enablement — that may already be deliberately customized for that tenant. A "reset to business type defaults" SuperAdmin action is reasonable to add but is not an automatic side effect of changing the type.
No hard delete on business_types — deactivate via is_active only, since tenants reference it.
general and physical_store get seeded into the new table with the current behavior preserved exactly — this is a refactor, not a behavior change, until Part 3 explicitly changes how that behavior is expressed.
Check for any other hardcoded TypeScript union type for business type values (beyond the loose string on AuthContext) that would block adding new values dynamically — relax if found.



Part 1 — Business type registry

1.1 Schema

sqlCREATE TABLE business_types (
  id               TEXT PRIMARY KEY,         -- e.g. 'general', 'physical_store'
  label            TEXT NOT NULL,            -- shown in the SuperAdmin selector
  config_defaults  JSONB NOT NULL DEFAULT '{}',
  is_active        BOOLEAN NOT NULL DEFAULT true,
  created_at       TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
  updated_at       TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now()
);

-- Seed existing values; config_defaults filled in during Part 3
INSERT INTO business_types (id, label, config_defaults) VALUES
  ('general', 'General', '{}'),
  ('physical_store', 'Physical Store', '{}');

ALTER TABLE tenants
  ADD CONSTRAINT fk_tenant_business_type
  FOREIGN KEY (business_type) REFERENCES business_types(id);

1.2 Backend

In netlify/functions/super-admin.mjs:


Replace the hardcoded ['general', 'physical_store'] validation (~line 192) with a query against business_types WHERE is_active = true.
Add: GET /business-types (list), POST /business-types (create), PATCH /business-types/:id (update label / config_defaults), PATCH /business-types/:id/deactivate.
On the existing tenant-update path, allow business_type to be changed on an existing tenant.


netlify/functions/utils/auth.mjs needs no change — it already selects business_type onto the JWT payload.

1.3 SuperAdmin UI (src/pages/SuperAdmin.tsx)


Replace the hardcoded two-option selector (~line 822) with options fetched from GET /business-types.
Add a "Business Types" screen: list (id, label, active toggle), create form (id + label), edit view for config_defaults — a raw JSON textarea is fine for now; show the expected shape (Part 3) as placeholder text.
On the tenant-edit screen, make business_type editable (not just set at creation), using the same dynamic options list.



Part 2 — Config resolution

Update getTenantConfig() (wherever it currently lives) to:


Look up the tenant's business_type.
Fetch the matching business_types.config_defaults.
Merge it onto whatever getTenantConfig() already returns, with the business-type config layered on top of the platform default.


For this round, the resolved object should include defaultEnabledModules (Part 3) — leave the shape open to add more keys later without migration.


Part 3 — Default module/feature access per business type

Investigate first: does nav rendering in src/App.tsx already derive from which modules are enabled (modules.ts / tenant_module_quotas), or is the businessType === 'physical_store' check (~lines 689, 725, 1010) a separate, independent switch from the module system? The original assessment describes physical_store's nav as "a stripped-down nav + a single DashboardStore route" — that's the same shape as "fewer modules enabled, one extra module enabled," which suggests this is likely already expressible through the existing module-gating system rather than needing a new config key.

If nav already derives from enabled modules:


Add a default module set to business_types.config_defaults, e.g. {"defaultEnabledModules": ["dashboard_store", "..."]}.
Apply it when a tenant is created with that business type (seed tenant_module_quotas accordingly).
Remove the now-redundant businessType === 'physical_store' checks in App.tsx in favor of letting nav render purely from module state.


If nav is currently independent of module state:


Make nav rendering derive from enabled modules — the one mechanism that already exists for "can this tenant see this" — rather than introducing a second, parallel one.
Then apply business-type defaults the same way as above.


If DashboardStore isn't currently wrapped as a module/feature at all (just a hardcoded route), formalize it as one, so it's toggled the same way as everything else rather than remaining a one-off exception.

Acceptance check: a physical_store tenant and a general tenant should see exactly the same nav/access as before this change — this is a refactor onto the existing module system, not a behavior change.


Sequencing

Build in order: 1 → 2 → 3. The registry (1) has to exist before config resolution (2) means anything, and resolution has to exist before the module-defaults work (3) can read from it.

Explicitly out of scope this round


Theme foundation — not built this round.
Tenant-level config overrides beyond what's in this plan — the merge order leaves room for this later without a schema rework.
Hard delete of business types — deactivate only.